'''''Hansuli Banker Upakatha''''' ({{lang-bn|হাঁসুলীবাঁকের উপকথা}}, first published: 1951)<ref name="Dalal2017">{{cite book|author=Roshen Dalal|title=India at 70: snapshots since Independenc|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JYswDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT140|date=23 August 2017|publisher=Penguin Random House India Private Limited|isbn=978-93-86815-37-8|pages=140–}}</ref> is a novel by [[Tarashankar Bandopadhyay]], set in 1941. The novel explores life in rural [[Bengal]], the realities of the [[Zamindar]]i system that was responsible for much of the social inequalities in Bengal, as well as the changes in social perceptions with time.

The novel was written and published in various versions between 1946 to 1951. In 1946, it was first appeared in a shorter version in a special annual [[Durga Puja|Durga festival]] issue of ''[[Anandabazar Patrika]]''. Later, the novel was expanded and revised over the following
five years, appearing in several editions during that time.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bandopadhyay|first=Tarashankar|title=The Tale of Hansuli Turn|url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/books/band14904/band14904-intro/band14904-intro.xml|chapter=Introduction|translator-last=Baer|translator-first=Ben Conisbee|year=2011|location=New York|publisher=Columbia University Press|page=vii|isbn=978-0-231-52022-5|via=[[De Gruyter]]}}{{Subscription required}}</ref>

The novel was translated into English as ''The Tale of Hansuli Turn'' by Ben Conisbee Baer, published 2011.<ref name="Comparative Literature">{{cite web | title=Benjamin Conisbee Baer | website=Comparative Literature | url=https://complit.princeton.edu/people/benjamin-conisbee-baer | access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref>

==Plot summary==
{{Empty section|date=October 2018}}
The plot is divided into 6 parts.

== Adaptation ==
[[Hansuli Banker Upakatha (film)|''Hasuli Banker Upakatha'' (film)]] was made in 1962 by [[Tapan Sinha]] based on this novel.

